add to_map function to vak.utils.labels

that maps a labelset to a dictionary. Has argument 'map_unlabeled'
that if True adds 'unlabeled' to the set and uses this "label" when
mapping the labelset from 0 to n labels.

Decide to do away with name 'silent_gap_label' and instead use
'unlabeled' which carries less baggage--you don't have to know
what a 'silent gap' is to understand it.

Also this now just forces the user to accept that the mapping will
be to consecutive integers from 0 to n; if for some reason users
don't want this they can specify their own mapping upon
instantiating a VocalizationDataset.

make changes to dataset.spect.from_files so it works without annotations

Instead of making a dummy list of tuples for 'annot_list', from_files makes
a dummy list of None that it pairs with spect_files. Then if
the 'annot' for a given tuple-pair is None, it does not try to unpack the
file attribute from the annotation and assign that to the Vocalization's
audio_path attribute (since we don't know the audio file from the annotation,
...that doesn't exist).

Also changed named 'spect_dict' to 'spect_kwargs' for clarity and to avoid
confusion with 'spect_dict', the dict-like object that provides access to the
'spect_path'

remove unnecessary validator in Vocalization class

remove validator that raised TypeError if annotation was not a list,
tuple, or Crowsetta sequence. Because (a) need to be able to default
to None if the Vocalization does not have annotation, and (b) the
annotation can only be a Crowsetta sequence (soon to be a Crowsetta
annotation object).

change vak.prep.prep signature and docstring

first parameter is now data_dir, with annot_format and labelset being
next parameters, and both now defaulting to None.

Main reason for this change is so we can `prep` datasets without
annotations (so we don't / can't specify labelset or annot_format)

Rewrite docstring to reflect these changes.
vak.prep.prep docstring specifies save_vds default is False

so that they all have labelset
add has_unlabeled function to vak.utils.labels
add test for has_unlabeled function to test_utils/test_labels.py
move/rephrase a comment in utils/labels.py

rewrite VocalizationDataset defaults and validators for labelset and labelmap

labelset:
if not assigned, and there are annotations, then labelset defaults to the
actual unique set of labels found in the annotations.
The validator raises an error if there are labels in actual unique set of labels
that are not found in labelset. However it does not raise an error if the actual
unique set of labels is a ("true") subset of labelset (because maybe this is one
set of vocalizations in which the particular label did not occur but it would
occur in others and we want to denote that).

labelmap:
if not assigned, and labelset is None, then default to None.
if not assigned, and labelset is not None, figure out if there are unlabeled
timebins and if so make a labelmap that includes 'unlabeled' (probably this
will usually be the case); otherwise just make labelmap without 'unlabeled'.
The validator raises an error if the set of keys in labelmap (minus 'unlabeled')
does not equal labelset.

make VocalizationDataset immutable, change load_spect and clear_spect methods

make immutable because it seems like this will require less constant error checking
(am I a functional programmer now?).

Have to change load_spect and clear_spect to return new instances of the
VocalizationDataset with only the attributes of interest 'mutated' using the
`attr.evolve` function.
rewrite tests after rewriting VocalizationDataset

remove skip_labels_not_in_labelset from dataset/audio.py

behavior now is that, if labelset is not None, then only use files
with labels in labelset

remove 'skip_files...' arg in test_dataset/test_audio.py

since I just removed that parameter from the dataset.audio.from_files function

remove unused imports in test_dataset/test_audio.py

remove skip_files_if_labels_not_in_labelset parameter from dataset.spect.from_files

fix default for VocalizationDataset.labelmap

now only gets set if labelset is not None *and* all Vocalizations have
both MetaSpects and Annotations associated with them
(because both MetaSpects and Annotations are required to determine by
default if there are unlabeled timebins, and so an 'unlabeled' key is
needed in labelmap)
fix matches_labelset validator for labelmap

dataset.prep sets annot_list to None if annot_format is None

There was missing check for pre-condition which would've caused an
error if 'annot_format' was None. Now it causes annot_list to also
default to None which enables making a VocalizatonDataset
without annotation.

remove 'skip_files...' parameter from dataset.prep

so that this function, like dataset.audio and dataset.spect that it

labels, .e.g for predicting labels from spectrograms

commit_message:
rewrite vak.cli.prep to be more general

now can create either split sets or just a single 'train' set.
Actually not sure if I should keep this but it works for now so
saving before I do anything else dumb.
rewrite tests in test_prep for newly rewritten vak/cli/prep.py
add safe_truncate function to utils.general
fix args in call to cli.prep in setup_scrips/remake_spects.py
rename setup_scripts/remake_spects.py to rerun_prep.py
fix args in call to cli.learncurve in setup_scrips/remake_results.py
rename setup_scripts/remake_results.py -> rerun_learncurve.py
update script names in Makefile
write docstring for VocalizationDataset.load_spects method

change behavior of VocalizationDataset.spects_list method

only works if instance has spectrograms loaded, otherwise raises ValueError
with (hopefully) informative error message

change load_spects so it returns VocalizationDataset with a labelmap

instead of using attr.evolve which keeps other attributes unchanged,
return new instance of VocalizationDataset where labelset=self.labelset,
but do not provide a value for labelmap to __init__ so that it defaults
to the appropriate mapping based on the labelset and the spectograms
(e.g. whether they have unlabeled segments so there should be an
'unlabeled' key in labelmap)

rewrite vak.cli.learncurve

- now uses VocalizationDataset
- add pre-conditions that make sure both val_vds_path and val_error_step
are specified, if either one is specified
- move generating/loading subsets up above loading validation set, and fix
some leftover errors from first attempt at this; now either generating or
loading previously generated indices for subsets of training data happens
in the same loop before the main training loop so that if either fails
this happens before training actually starts
- during main loop, reshaped/scaled data is only saved if `save_transformed_data` is True
- remove 'if __main__' section at end of file that ran function as a test
setup_scripts/rerun_prep.py checks if config file exists
setup_scripts/rerun_learncurve.py checks if config file exists

remove attributes from DataConfig and related code in parse_data_config

- removed attributes that are no longer used:
  + skip_files_with_labels_not_in_labelset
    - because behavior now is to do this automatically, if 'labelset' is specified
  + silent_gap_label
    - because VocalizationDataset determines whether there is a need for 'unlabeled'
      automatically, no need for user to specify in DataConfig
  + all_labels_are_int

add source_annot_map function to vak.dataset.annot

takes list of source files and annotations, and returns a dictionary
that maps each source file to its annotation.

Raises errors if:
- an annotation cannot be mapped to a source file
- multiple source files can be mapped to a single annotation
- if some source files are not mapped to annotations

Used by dataset.audio.to_spect to make sure that annotations passed in can be
mapped to audio files passed in as list, or to all audio files found in
some directory

utils.general._files_from_dir sorts glob output before returning

because order of list returned by glo is not guaranteed otherwise

rewrite dataset.audio.to_spect

main change is that:
- checking labelset no longer happens inside nested function
  that is used to parallelize spectrogram file creation

because the function would issue a warning then return, and this would create
None entries in the list computed by Dask. Instead we do any labelset checking
before the parallel creation of spect files

- added source_annot_map function calls

because in process of fixing first issue, realized that ordering of audio files
found with glob was not guaranteed, and so making a dictionary that was just
the zip of audio files found + an annotation list passed by user could create a
mismatch of audio with annotation; so had to add a function that maps them to
each other and fails gracefully if it can't do so

add audio + related files to test_data/cbins/gy6or6/032312

specifically, files where there are labels not in labelset

These will be used to test that filtering by labelset works as expected

helper assert function now checks that, if labelset was used, that only files
that have labels limited to those found in labelset are made into spectrograms.
Tests pass after rewriting dataset.audio.to_spect

fix bug in source_annot_map

Now make a copy of source_files list and pop items off that copy instead of
the original. Popping off the original was causing bugs in downstream
functions that use the original for other purposes.

But in this function we pop off items so we can check whether all source files
were matched to annotations--if there's no items in the list then we know we
matched them all. Making a copy is a cheap fix that lets use this approach.

rewrite vak.dataset.spect.from_files

following roughly same logic of just rewritten dataset.audio.to_spect

- first check if we got a dir, if we did then get files (spect files in this
case)
- now check for spect_files (which we might have just got from dir, or from
user input)
  + and map files to annotations if user gave us any
    + and if user gave labelset, use that to filter out annotations
    containing labels not in labelset
- now that we have mapping from files to annotation (or maybe user gave it to
us already), we validate what's in all the files
  + can't do this very cleanly in the nested function that Dask uses to
  parallelize because we want user to get error messages without a giant
  dump of Dask stack (at least I don't know how to do this).
  + and we don't want a bunch of Nones in what Dask computes in parallel which
  result when the nested function returns early because some criterion wasn't
  met
- once we validate go ahead and make the VocalizationDataset in parallel
use pathlib in test_dataset.test_spect; add line breaks in long lines

filter by labelset in vak.dataset.prep

this is also done by audio.to_spect and spect.from_files but decided to
*also** do it here before calling those functions; this is repeating yourself,
but the idea is that user might call those functions without calling prep,
*and* we want prep to filter first just in case some weird difference in logic
b/t audio.to_spect and spect.from_files gives us different results when they
handle the filtering

I dunno, maybe it's redundant and dumb

rewrite annot.source_annot_map again to fix bug

was giving 'found multiple matches' error with koumura .wav files, because
when you take stem of a file named '0.wav' (i.e., '0') then it's going to match
every file name that has a '0' in it, if you match by saying
"if stem in file name"

Rewrite looks for an exact match between stems of all source files names
and stem of the file specified in the annotation

rewrite _recursive_stem in dataset.annotation

was recursively stemming too much when filenames had time stamps with
units separated by periods; need to have a 'smarter' loop that stops as
soon as the extension split from the stem is a known audio file extension.
This works for audio files *and* for spectrogram files whose name is just
"audio file + array file extension (.mat or .npz)"

vak.dataset.prep filters by labelset in audio files only

because if user is making dataset from audio files and we **don't** do this,
then there can be entries in the annotation list that were not made into
spectrogram files because they had labels not in labelset, and the call to
source_annot_map in spect.from_files will crash when it can't find a non-
existent spect file that should map to this annotation

This is only a problem in this particular situation; won't matter if user
doesn't pass labelset, or is making dataset from spectrogram files not audio
files (since spect.from_files would handle the filtering by labelset)

add two utility functions to vak.io.dataframe

- validate_and_get_timebin_dur -- checks there is a single unique
  value for the duration of time bins in all the spectograms in the
  dataset, using the 'timebin_dur' column from the dataframe.
  Returns that value.
- split_dur -- get duration of a split in the dataset. Sums value of
  'duration' column for only the rows where 'split' column == split specified
  by user in call to function.
- both functions make vak.cli.train more concise and can be used elsewhere

when config specifies 'labelset' but config has a [PREDICT] section,
raises a warning and changes 'labelset' to None

because without this, dataframe.from_files will try to check whether
the annotations for each audio file have only labels from labelset,
but since there's no annotation for those files (we're trying to
predict the annotations, presumably), the annotation will be "None" and
this will result in an error

add function 'from_df' to util/labels.py

encapsulates control flow logic for getting labels associated with
each row of a dataframe

- if unique annotation file for each row, load each file and get labels
  out of it, return list of labels
- else if a single annotation file for all rows, load that file, test
  whether we get back a list of annotations equal to the number of
  rows, and if so, sort by 'audio_path' of each row and return
  list of labels
- else raise an error because we don't know what to do

change behavior of labelset_from_toml_value converter

Now always returns labelset as single-character strings
(e.g. {'a', 'b', '1', '3', '5'}). Handles strings like "abcde"
and a "range string" like "range: 1-20, 22" as before, but now
casts lists of ints to string, and parses each element of a
list of strings according to the rules for single strings--i.e.,
labelset=["range:1-3", "a-"] would become {'1', '2', '3', 'a', '-'}.

rewrite source_annot_map

so that it maps source files to annotations, not the other way around.

The function will no longer raise an error if it cannot map every
annotation in the input list `annot_list` to a source file in the
input list `source_files`.

Now it only raises an error if it cannot map every file in
`source_files` to an annotation (or some other pathological condition
occurs, e.g. multiple annotaiton files have audio_file attributes
that yield the same stem, which is what is used to match them with
the source files).

then continue, because as long as there at least as many annotations
as there are rows, we can attempt to match each

change how spect.to_dataframe filters by labelset

spect.to_dataframe assumes that if user specifies a labelset,
they want to filter any source files out of the dataframe
for which the corresponding annotation has labels that are **not**
in the specified labelset.

E.g., if labelset is {'a', 'b', 'c', 'd', 'e'} and one file has
annotation with a label 'q', we don't want to include that in the
dataset (maybe it is some rarely occurring event we don't want to
label or don't have enough examples to classify well)

the logic for doing this was inside the loop for validating

commit_message: fixup #158 TrainConfig docstring

change how Model saves checkpoints, fix #157 & #159

Overall this commit moves most logic for checkpointing
out of `fit` and into the `_train` method.
This is because we want to validate and/or save
checkpoints based on the global step, not the epoch,
see discussion in #157, #158, and #159.

Major differences:
- add attributes to Model
  + Model.__init__ now adds attributes ckpt_path,
  max_val_acc, max_val_acc_ckpt_path, patience, and
  patience_counter to self
  + so `fit` can set them and `_train` can access them
- move logic from `fit` method to `_train`
  + `fit` now simply iterates through epochs calling `train`
- make `fit` call `self.save` after the last epoch,
  addressing #157
  + this is the only real "training" logic in `fit` now
- change logic for checkpointing as per #159
  + save a "backup" checkpoint on every checkpoint step
  + save a separate "max-val_acc" checkpoint on every validation
    step, *if* accuracy on the validation set improves
- remove `fit` method parameters `single_ckpt` and `save_best_only`
  + no longer used, since we save the backup checkpoint
    no matter what, and always save the max-val-acc checkpoint
    whenever we're using a validation set
remove save_only_single_checkpoint_file

* this change will make it possible for a new dataset

  dataset can return them when its `__getitem__` method

rewrite _eval method of vak.model

so that it works with output of
EvalItemTransform, instead of working the
same way as the training data set.

At a high level: each "batch" is one item
from the dataset class, i.e. one spectrogram
transformed so it is a stack of windows.
We remove the batch dimension (of size 1),
get the predictions, flatten them, remove any
predictions made on padding, and then
use the result to compute any metrics like
accuracy.

change/fix WindowDataset spect vector logic

- these changes should make the duration method return
  the expected duration, and make the class slightly
  more flexible, because valid indices for the start of
  a window are now determined solely by x_inds
- the way the class worked before, both spect_id_vector
  and spect_inds_vector for each spectrogram in the dataset
  had a length equal to the spectrogram's length, minus
  the window size
- but this makes it complicated to "crop" them using
  the labeled time bins vector--which is what the
  "safe_truncate" from version 0.2 did, and what the
  "crop_duration" static method does--since those
  spect vectors won't be as long as the labeled time
  bins vector
- so now they are simply the same length as the spectrogram
- and instead of x_inds being just as long as them, it is
  constructed on the fly with valid and invalid indices
- i.e. for each spectrogram in the dataset, we take the same
  length we computed previously, the total spectrogram length
  minus the window length, and we make a new x_inds vector
  with those indices. The x_inds vector is the same length
  as the spect_id_vector and spect_inds_vector for this
  spectrogram, and any element with an index greater than
  the last valid index is set to a constant value
  INVALID_WINDOW_VAL
- this makes it possible to simply remove all the elements
  with INVALID_WINDOW_VAL from x_inds before returning.
  The "length" of the dataset (__len__) is still the number
  of elements in x_inds, but the duration is now
  the timebin duration * the length of spect_inds_vector,
  which even when cropped still includes the entire length
  of the last window, so it will return the appropriate
  duration.

BUG: correct x_inds after crop from front, fix #217

- the WindowDataset staticmethod
  `crop_spect_vectors_keep_classes`
  crops the vectors used to represent the
  dataset of windows to a fixed duration
  + `spect_id_vector` and `spect_inds_vector`
    which are the length of the dataset in timebins,
    and represent the spectrogram ID and valid
    indices within that spectrogram where windows
    can start, respectively
- it first crops "from the back", finding
  all time bins greater than the specified
  duration
- but if, after cropping off those time bins,
  not all labels in the labelset are in the
  resulting cropped window dataset, the function
  tries to crop "from the front", removing
  the same duration of time bins from the start.
- there was a bug where the `x_inds` vector was
  not updated after cropping from the front
- this produced an IndexError because a there would
  be values in `x_inds` that were greater than the
  actual length of `spect_id_vector`
  and `spect_inds_vector`
- this fix adds logic that adjusts values in `x_inds`
  ,when cropping from the front only,
  so that values start from zero again

add third way to crop to WindowDataset method

add logic at end of the `crop_spect_vectors_keep_classes`
method that looks for unlabeled segments and removes them.

The method still tries to first crop the specified duration
from the end, then from the begnning. If neither of those
work, this additional logic, crops unlabeled segments
larger than `window_size`.

This is done by preventing training windows from
starting at points within the silence segments.
Since silence segments can follow non-silence segments
or precede them, the amount of data being ignored
actually depend on whether the silence segment
happens to be right in the beginning of the file
or right in the end. We make sure to account for that.

behavior of ``vak.config.converts.labelset_from_toml_value``
function stays the same when the value for the ``labelset``
option in a toml file is a string, but when it is a list,
they are now processed like so:
any multi-character elementthat is not a "rangestr" now stays as is.

The function no longer requires the list to be
either all ints or all str.

because the converter function could just return a None
if the list was not all ints or all strs).

converts any "rangestr",
and leaves anything else (single/multi-character string) untouched.

- add `previous_run_path` parameter to `vak.core.learncurve`
- when `previous_run_path` is specified, function looks for
  in that path for .csv files representing training data subsets
  created by a previous run of `learncurve`

  which returns a dictionary mapping training data subset
  durations to the .csv paths representing different subsets,
  `train_dur_csv_paths`
- previously `train_dur_csv_paths` was created every time by
  a code block in the middle of the main `learning_curve` function
- factored that code block out into a function called

- so, `learning_curve` now checks if `previous_run_path` is
  specified, and if so, gets `train_dur_csv_paths` from that

rewrite & rename function in split/algorithms/validate.py

- no longer convert all durations to non-negative numbers
  + **because the "algorithm" functions that call this one
    to validate specified durations need to "see"
    when one of the splits is specified as -1, so that
    they can determine whether the
    computed splits have the appropriate duration --
    turns out if you just set the "-1 duration" to be
    "total duration - specified duration",
    you can end up in a situation
    where you're never able to actually find a split
    for which the "-1 duration" actually equals "total - specified".
    E.g. if train = 3 seconds and test = -1,
    and the total duration of the dataset is 10 seconds,
    but any combination of x vocalizations in the dataset > 3 seconds,
    then you can never find a test set that >= 7 seconds.
    I did not totally verify that was the source of the bug,
    e.g., by recording size of each split, but making these fixes
    seems to resolve the issue where any -1 split fails
    because we exceed max # of iterations.
- accordingly, rename `validate_durations_convert_nonnegative` to just
  `validate_split_durations`
  + and change call to this function in `vak.split` to match
- rename `vds_dur` parameter to `dataset_dur` for clarity
  + the name `vds` is a holdover from when we had the
    `VocalizationDataset` classes.

rewrite `vak.split.algorithms.bruteforce`

for consistency + clarity.
Mostly fixing issues spotted while writing
unit tests.

- use dictionaries throughout,
  where keys are split names
  + to iterate over them and thus avoid
    repetitive code blocks that just apply the
    exact same logic to different splits
  + and to remove similarly repetitive code
    at the top where we initialize lists
    for each split
- remove `durs_labels_list`, a list of
  tuples
  + realize can just index into either
    durs or labels with the current 'ind'
    and this makes the code clearer
- insert pre-condition that makes sure
  durs and labels are the same length
  + getting rid of `durs_label_list` also
    lets us avoid the error where
    zip truncates one of lists silently
    if they are different sizes.
    But better to explicitly check and
    raise a clear error instead of
    failing non-obviously.
- change logic at end so we always return
  None if the split is empty -- instead of
  sometimes returning an empty list, a
  side effect of the complicated way we
  initialized at the top of the function

bug: fix how `lbl_tb2segments` computes on/offsets

currently the `lbl_tb2segments` function
approximates the onsets and offsets
in seconds by setting them to the time "between"
bins, i.e. half the width of the timebin;
this is the best estimate we can make,
given that we are assigning labels to each
timebin.

But when the input has an onset at index 0
or an offset at the last timebin, this produces
an estimate that is "outside" the valid times
in the vector of timebins.

BUG: fix how `spect.to_dataframe` handles annot_path

change `spect.to_dataframe` so that when there is no
annotation--e.g. when `prep`aring a dataset for
`predict`ion--it sets the `annot_path` to `np.nan`
instead of `None`

this prevents errors in unit testing where comparing
the dataframe returned by `core.prep` with the
dataframe loaded with `pd.read_csv` gives false positives
for "not equal"

and in general avoids needing to special-case
how this column is loaded. Just keep it as np.nan
when there's no annotation.
This is also faster than having a `pandas.Series` of
`None` which would be treated as `numpy.object` datatype.
Probably doesn't matter for most use cases
but might to start matter with giant datasets.

BUG: fix how `learncurve` handles `previous_run_path`, #316

When running `learncurve` with a `previous_run_path`,
we currently re-use the vectors that the `WindowSize`
dataset class uses to ensure the windows we grab our valid.
Those vectors are saved as .npy files on the previous run,
and right now the `train_dur_csv_paths_from_dir` function
just copies them to the new `results_dir`
so they get re-used.

But this causes a bug when we use a different window size.
Since which windows are valid depends on the window size,
of course.

The fix is to have `train_dur_csv_paths_from_dir` call
`WindowDataset.spect_vectors_from_df` instead of
using the saved `spect_vectors` from
the `previous_run_path`.

Since the `spect_vectors_from_df` method is
deterministic given the same `subset_df`,
this shouldn't change behavior when window size
is the same. But when window size changes,
we now generate the correct `spect_vectors`

BUG: fix how `train_dur_csv_paths.from_dir` orders replicates, fixes #340

- refactor `train_dur_csv_paths`
  - factor out code from `train_dur_csv_paths.from_dir`
    that uses `previous_run_path` to build
    dictionary mapping training set durations to
    dataset csv paths into function `_dict_from_dir`
    + this makes it possible to unit test this function alone
    + to make sure we address
      https://github.com/NickleDave/vak/issues/330
  - factor out functions from `train_dur_csv_paths.from_df`
    that specify names for:
    + `train_dur` directories -- these are made within the
      results path directory, one for each specified training
      set duration
    + `replicate` directories, made within each `train_dur` directory
    + `subset` .csv filename, one for each replicate
    + this allows us to make expected names explicit +
      test they get used and use these in fixtures

- add tests/test_core/test_train_dur_csv_paths.py
  including tests for `_dict_from_dir` function
  that specifically tests whether issues in
  https://github.com/NickleDave/vak/issues/330
  are fixed
  + to do so, create a `tmp_previous_run_path_factory` fixture
    that uses "directory/file naming" functions that
    were factored out of `train_dur_csv_paths.from_dfr`
  + this lets us create a temporary "previous run" with enough
    (fake) replicates to make sure we get numeric ordering
    (1, 2, ..., 9, 10) instead of alphabetical ordering
    (1, 10, 2, ...)

commit_message:
DEV/CI: add and use `codecov`, fix #86

- add `pytest-cov` as dev dependency
  + upper bound Python as <3.9 to get `coverage` to install
- make ci.yml run pytest with --cov option, save xml report
- set .gitignore to ignore coverage outputs
DOC: add coverage badge to README
CLN: make minor edit to `Model._predict` docstring
CLN: fix rst formatting in window_dataset docstring
CLN: fix log statement in core.eval
TST: add test_metrics/test_distance/test_functional.py, fix #354

BUG: fix Levenshtein distance implementation, fix #355

fixes a relatively minor bug in how Levenshtein distance
is computed

Originally we used a vectorized Numpy implementation,
the fifth algorithm under Python in this Wikibook:
https://en.wikibooks.org/wiki/Algorithm_Implementation/Strings/Levenshtein_distance#Python

but this implementation has a bug:
https://en.wikibooks.org/wiki/Talk:Algorithm_Implementation/Strings/Levenshtein_distance#Bug_in_vectorized_(5th)_version

I did not estimate how often this could cause a miscalculation.
But the previous implementation did pass all other tests I added --
only the example given in that discussion caused distance
to be off by 1.

I modified the implementation to match this version from `pylev`
https://github.com/toastdriven/pylev/blob/e79ef6814c51046fee635a2a2316f8a57fa1e697/pylev.py#L156

It now passes all tests including the case described
in that discussion.

CLN: add edge-case handling to `segment_error_rate`

- return 0 when both `y_pred` and `y_true` have length zero
- when `y_true` has length zero, but `y_pred` does not, raise
  a ValueError explaining segment error rate is not defined
  + only caught this when adding tests
  + usually we're not trying to predict a sequence with length zero
  + but adding error handling anyway
DOC: update CHANGELOG after merging #356

ENH: add vak/nn sub-package with dice loss

- add sub-package vak/nn
  - that includes a loss sub-package,
    with an implementation of Dice Loss adapted from
    the `kornia` library.
    Key difference is, this implementation of Dice Loss
    is "1-dimensional", i.e., it operates on a
    time series, a sequence of T labeled frames, instead
    of an image with HxW labeled pixels.
  - also add `functional` module with a `one_hot` function,
    adapted from `kornia` as well.
- add tests for all added code, similarly adapted from `kornia`
